Tips at Restaurants

In this homework we will use the tips data set. This data set is part of the reshape2 package. You can load the data set by executing the command:

data(tips, package="reshape2")
library(ggplot2)

If you do not have available the package reshape2, issue install.packages('reshape2') to install it. The information contained in the data is collected by one waiter, who recorded over the course of a season information about each tip he received working in one restaurant. See ?tips for a description of all of the variables.

numParty <- length(tips$size)

  1. What are the types of variables in the data frame tips? Include the code and also explain verbally.
sapply(tips, class)
## total_bill        tip        sex     smoker        day       time 
##  "numeric"  "numeric"   "factor"   "factor"   "factor"   "factor" 
##       size 
##  "integer"

This means that total bill is a numeric value so a number, tip is also a number, sex is a factor because it is non numeric and you have male or female, smoker is also a factor because it is just yes or no, day is a factor because it just gives us lunch or dinner, and size is an integer because it is the number of people so you can only have a whole number.

  1. How does the tipping amount (tip) depend on the overall bill (total_bill)? Use the ggplot2 package to make a chart. Describe the relationship in words.
ggplot(tips, aes(x=total_bill, y=tip)) + geom_point(shape=16, size=3)

There is a fairly good correlation between tiprate and total bill where if people have a low bill they tip less and if they have a high bill they tip more. However, aside from a few points that stray, they are pretty proportional in their tip percentage.

  1. Describe at least two types of anomalies in the previous plot. What do they mean? One anomalie is where someone only had about a $7 bill yet still tipped about $5, about a 72% tip. Another is on a $45ish bill, they only tipped $2.50 which is about 5%. In our data, the average tip is about 16% and these both stray from that, especially the generous tipper.

  2. Introduce a variable tiprate into the data set which stands for the rate of tips. What is the average rate for tips? Explain verbally.

tiprate <- tips$tip/tips$total_bill
mean(tiprate)
## [1] 0.1608026

The average tip is about 16%.

  1. Make a boxplot of the tip rate by time. The x-axis should be ordered by lunch and then dinner. Use ggplot2 to make a chart. Verbally explain the chart.
ggplot(data = tips, aes(x = time, y = tiprate)) +
    geom_boxplot() + 
    coord_flip()

The tiprate is pretty much the same for both meals with dinner having a few higher outliers.

  1. How does smoking behavior and gender of the person who pays impact the relationship between tip and total bill? Find a visualization that incorporates all four variables. Interpret the result.
ggplot(aes(x = total_bill, y = tip,
           colour=sex), data=tips) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~smoker)

In these plots we can see that their is a stronger correlation in the plot of non smokers and the smokers plot is more spread out. In this plot we can also see that men usually have the higher total bill but that the tiprate is still pretty proportional among men and women in the non smokers. Tiprate on the smokers plot is definitely more scattered but doesnt really tell us anything about the difference between men and women in this one as they look to be about the same.

  1. Use ggplot2 to find a graphical summary of the relationship between day of the week and gender of the person paying the bill. What can you say about this relationship?
ggplot(tips, aes(x = day)) + geom_bar() +facet_wrap(~sex)

In this we can see that men mostly pay the bill Friday, Saturday, and Sunday but women pay the bill slightly more on Thursdays.
